        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "2. Collisions in the Drude model, as in kinetic theory, are instantaneous events that abruptly alter the velocity of an electron. Drude attributed them to the electrons bouncing off the impenetrable ion cores (rather than to electron-electron collisions. the analogue of the predominant collision mechanism in an ordinary gas). We shall find later that electron-electron scattering is indeed one of the least important of the several scattering mechanisms in a metal, except under unusual conditions. However,"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                102,
                821,
                856,
                934
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "page_header",
            "content": {
                "page_header_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Basic Assumptions of the Drude Model"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                527,
                46,
                828,
                65
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "page_number",
            "content": {
                "page_number_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "5"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                842,
                47,
                860,
                63
            ]
        }
