        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "One generally eliminates the dependence of R on the shape of the wire by introducing a quantity characteristic only of the metal of which the wire is composed. The resistivity "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\rho"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "is defined to be the proportionality constant between the electric field E at a point in the metal and the current density j that it induces10."
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                146,
                117,
                920,
                192
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "equation_interline",
            "content": {
                "math_content": "{ \\bf E } = \\rho { \\bf j } .\\tag{1.3}",
                "math_type": "latex",
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/a12c68336565ccfb6a09b737d3601aee62ee5f7687b447ba0d9f5df5d42dfa46.jpg"
                }
            },
            "bbox": [
                489,
                199,
                570,
                219
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "The current density j is a vector. parallel to the flow of charge, whose magnitude is the amount of charge per unit time crossing a unit area perpendicular to the flow. Thus if a uniform current I fows through a wire of length L and cross-sectional area A, the current density will be "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "j = I , A"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Since the potential drop along the wire will be "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "V = E L"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ", Eq. (1.3) gives "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "V = I \\rho L / . 4 ."
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ",and hence "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "R = \\rho L / A"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                146,
                228,
                920,
                321
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "If n electrons per unit volume all move with velocity v, then the current density they give rise to will be parallel to v. Furthermore, in a time dt the electrons will advance by a distance v dt in the direction of v, so that "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "n ( \\tau d t ) A"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "electrons will cross an area A perpendicular to the direction of flow. Since each electron carries a charge "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "- e ,"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "the charge crossing 4 in the time dt will be "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "- n e t A d t ,"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "and hence the current density is"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                146,
                320,
                920,
                431
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "equation_interline",
            "content": {
                "math_content": "{ \\bf j } = - n e { \\bf v } .\\tag{1.4}",
                "math_type": "latex",
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/d1ed7744694d8df06606ee154540371667b602bcb9bdf7ace661d488a9b18359.jpg"
                }
            },
            "bbox": [
                477,
                431,
                582,
                448
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "At any point in a metal, electrons are always moving in a variety of directions with a variety of thermal energies. The net current density is thus given by (1.4), where v is the average electronic velocity. In the absence of an electric field, electrons are as likely to be moving in any one direction as in any other, v averages to zero, and, as expected, there is no net electric current density. In the presence of a field E, however, there will be a mean electronic velocity directed opposite to the feld (the electronic charge being negative), which we can compute as follows:"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                143,
                459,
                920,
                589
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Consider a typical electron at time zero. Let t be the time elapsed since its last collision. Its velocity at time zero will be its velocity "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\Psi _ { 0 }"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "immediately after that collision plus the additional velocity "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "- e \\mathbf { E } t / m"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "it has subsequently acquired. Since we assume that an electron emerges from a collision in a random direction, there will be no contribution from "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "{ \\bf v } _ { 0 }"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "to the average electronic velocity, which must therefore be given entirely by the average of "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "- e \\mathbf { E } t / m"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "However, the average of t is the relaxation time . Therefore"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                143,
                589,
                923,
                718
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "equation_interline",
            "content": {
                "math_content": "\\mathbf { \\boldsymbol { \\nu } } _ { \\mathrm { a v g } } = - \\ \\frac { e \\mathbf { E } \\tau } { m } ; ~ \\mathbf { \\ j } = \\left( \\frac { n e ^ { 2 } \\tau } { m } \\right) \\mathbf { \\boldsymbol { \\mathbf { E } } } .\\tag{1.5}",
                "math_type": "latex",
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/c78d659d8694068c112cac9531c70a16810200b2881e78b23b4634c08aa58543.jpg"
                }
            },
            "bbox": [
